2022-10-08

igraph

igraph is a R library for analyzing graphs/networks.

There are alternatives but igraph has most of the fundamental measures already implemented.

Read the documentation carefully and test measures/metrics yourself on toy models to be sure that you understood the process used for computing the measure.

Installing igraph

#install.packages("igraph")

library(igraph)
## 
## Attaching package: 'igraph'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

##     union

g1

## + edges from dd55b5f:

Creating another toy graph

# now with 10 vertices
g2 <- graph( edges=c(1,2, 2,3, 3,1, 4,1, 10,1), n=10 , directed = F)
plot(g2)

Creating another toy graph

A directed graph with three edges

g3 <- graph( c("John", "Jim", "Jim", "Jill", "Jill", "John")) # named vertices
# When the edge list has vertex names, the number of nodes is not needed
plot(g3)

Creating another toy graph

g4 <- graph( c("John", "Jim", "Jim", "Jack", "Jim", "Jack", "John", "John"), 
             isolates=c("Jesse", "Janis", "Jennifer", "Justin") )  
# In named graphs we can specify isolates by providing a list of their names.
plot(g4)

A better visualization

plot(g4, edge.arrow.size=.5, vertex.color="gold", vertex.size=15,

Add attributes to the network, vertices, or edges

V(g4)$name # automatically generated when we created the network
## [1] "John"     "Jim"      "Jack"     "Jesse"    "Janis"    "Jennifer" "Justin"
V(g4)$gender <- c("male", "male", "male", "male", "female", "female", "male")
E(g4)$type <- "email" # Edge attribute, assign "email" to all edges
E(g4)$weight <- sample(10,ecount(g4))    # Edge weight, setting all existing edges to 10

E(g4)$weight

Simplify

g4
## IGRAPH 1e83c6b DNW- 7 4 -- Email Network
## + attr: name (g/c), name (v/c), gender (v/c), color (v/c), type (e/c),
## | weight (e/n)
## + edges from 1e83c6b (vertex names):
## [1] John->Jim  Jim ->Jack Jim ->Jack John->John
  • g4 has two edges going from Jim to Jack, and a loop from John to himself.
  • We can simplify our graph to remove loops & multiple edges between the same nodes.

Simplify

g4_simplified <- simplify(g4, remove.multiple = T, remove.loops = F, 
                          edge.attr.comb=list(weight="sum", type="ignore"))
#this way of simplifying doesn't keep EDGE multiplicity
g4_simplified
## IGRAPH a2e3662 DNW- 7 3 -- Email Network
## + attr: name (g/c), name (v/c), gender (v/c), color (v/c), weight (e/n)
## + edges from a2e3662 (vertex names):
## [1] John->John John->Jim  Jim ->Jack
E(g4_simplified)$weight
## [1] 10  9 12

Simplify

But if we assign a weight attribute (unitary) to each edge then simplifying counts their multiplicity

E(g4)$weight = 1

g4_simplified <- simplify(g4, remove.multiple = T, remove.loops = F, 
                          edge.attr.comb=list(weight="sum", type="ignore"))
#this keeps edge attributes because we assigned them in advance
g4_simplified
## IGRAPH 60418fd DNW- 7 3 -- Email Network
## + attr: name (g/c), name (v/c), gender (v/c), color (v/c), weight (e/n)
## + edges from 60418fd (vertex names):
## [1] John->John John->Jim  Jim ->Jack
E(g4_simplified)$weight
## [1] 1 1 2

Simplify

Finally we obtain

g4_simplified <- simplify(g4, remove.multiple = T, remove.loops = T, edge.attr.comb=list(weight="sum", type="ignore"))

plot(g4_simplified, edge.arrow.size=.5, vertex.color=V(g4)$color, vertex.size=15, 
     vertex.frame.color="gray", vertex.label.color="black", 
     vertex.label.cex=1.5, vertex.label.dist=2, edge.curved=0.2)

Graph Models

  • Erdos-Renyi random graph

There are two possible models for creating a random graph that are called gnp and gnm

  • The first model uses as a parameter the probability of connection between two nodes
  • The second model uses as a parameter the number of edges

Graph Models

In the case of gnp the number of edges changes over realizations, in the gnm it doesn’t

erP <- sample_gnp(n=100, p=0.01, directed = F) 
plot(erP, vertex.size=6, vertex.label=NA)## ('n' is number of nodes, 'p' is the number of edges) 

c(ecount(erP),ecount(sample_gnp(n=100, p=0.01)),ecount(sample_gnp(n=100, p=0.01)))
## [1] 47 39 52

Graph Models

Let’s do the same thing with gnm let’s say that \(p = 0.01\) then \(0.01 = \frac{2m}{n(n-1)}\) thus \(\frac{n(n-1)}{2}*p = m\) and \(m = 49.5\).

\(\frac{n(n-1)}{2}\) is the maximum number of links in a network with \(n\) nodes

erM <- sample_gnm(n = 100, m = 50, directed = F)
plot(erM, vertex.size=6, vertex.label=NA)

Graph Models

Erdos-Renyi with number of nodes \(n\) and mean degree \(\overline{k}\) as parameters

\(\overline{k} = 2m/n\)

gnm_mean_degree <- function(n,mean_k){
  m = round((n*mean_k)/2)
  g = sample_gnm(n, m) }
g <- gnm_mean_degree(50,6)
plot(g, vertex.size = 6, vertex.label = NA, vertex.color = "magenta")

Graph Models

Evolution of the Largest Connected Component of an Erdos-Renyi random graph

er_lcc <- c()

for(p in seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01)){
  er = sample_gnp(100,p, directed = F, loops = F)
  #plot(ws, layout = layout.circle(ws))
  lcc = max(components(er)$csize)
 # print(cc)
  er_lcc = c(er_lcc, lcc)
  }
plot(x = seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01), y = er_lcc/vcount(er), xlab = "p", ylab = "LCC")

Graph Models

The previous simulations produces a different Erdos-Renyi graph each time. To create a reproducible simulation we should set the seed that generated the random sequence.

er_lcc <- c()
set.seed(100)
for(p in seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01)){
  er = sample_gnp(100,p, directed = F, loops = F)
  lcc = max(components(er)$csize)
  er_lcc = c(er_lcc, lcc)
  }
plot(x = seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01), y = er_lcc/vcount(er), xlab = "p", ylab = "LCC")

Graph Models

Let’s do a better visualization

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
tibble(p = seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01), LCC = er_lcc/vcount(er)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = p, y = LCC)) + geom_point() + theme_classic()

Graph Models

Now let’s see what happens when we compute both the size of the lcc and the average path length

er_lcc <- c()
er_avpl <- c()
set.seed(100)
for(p in seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01)){
  er = sample_gnp(100,p, directed = F, loops = F)
  lcc = max(components(er)$csize)
  avpl <- average.path.length(er)
  er_lcc = c(er_lcc, lcc)
  er_avpl = c(er_avpl,avpl)
}
#plot(x = seq(from = 0, to =  1, by =0.01), y = er_lcc/vcount(er), xlab = "p", ylab = "LCC")

Graph Models

Watts-Strogatz small-world graph

# Creates a lattice with 'dim' dimensions of 'size' nodes each, and rewires edges 
# randomly with probability 'p'. You can allow 'loops' and 'multiple' edges.
# The neighborhood in which edges are connected is 'nei'.
sw <- sample_smallworld(dim=1,size=20,nei=4,p=0)#4 links on the left and 4 on the right
plot(sw, vertex.size=6, vertex.label=NA, layout=layout_in_circle)

Graph Models

Watts-Strogatz small-world graph

# Creates a lattice with 'dim' dimensions of 'size' nodes each, and rewires edges 
# randomly with probability 'p'. You can allow 'loops' and 'multiple' edges.
# The neighborhood in which edges are connected is 'nei'.
sw <- sample_smallworld(dim=1,size=20,nei=4,p=0.05)
plot(sw, vertex.size=6, vertex.label=NA, layout=layout_in_circle, loops = F, multiple = F)

Graph Models

What happens to the degree distribution when we rewire shuffling one of the two endpoints?

bind_rows(tibble(deg=degree(sample_smallworld(dim=1,size=20,nei=4,p=0)),type = "p0"),
          tibble(deg=degree(sample_smallworld(dim=1,size=20,nei=4,p=0.1)),type = "p0.1"),
          tibble(deg=degree(sample_smallworld(dim=1,size=20,nei=4,p=0.2)),type = "p0.2")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=deg)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(vars(type)) + theme_classic()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Graph Models

ws_cc = numeric()
ws_av = numeric()
#fattori di normalizzazione
normcc <- transitivity(sample_smallworld(1, 100, 4, 0, loops = F, multiple = F))
normav <- average.path.length(sample_smallworld(1, 100, 4, 0, loops = F, multiple = F))
#clustering coefficient & av path length VS rewiring probability
for(p in seq(from = 0.0, to =  1, by =0.0001)){#small step size
  ws = sample_smallworld(1, 100, 4, p, loops = F, multiple = F)
  cc = transitivity(ws)
  av = average.path.length(ws)
  ws_cc = c(ws_cc, cc)
  ws_av = c(ws_av, av)
}

Graph Models

The x-axis has a logarithmic scale

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
p_plot <- seq(from = 0.0, to =  1, by =0.0001)
tibble(x = c(p_plot,p_plot),y = c(ws_cc/normcc,ws_av/normav),
       type = c(rep("cc",length(p_plot)),rep("av",length(p_plot)))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y, color = type)) + geom_point(size = 0.1, alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_x_log10(breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
   labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  theme_classic()
